\section{Mayer-Vietoris LES connecting hom (iter-021)}

After Section~\ref{sec:moduleK_shortexact} (the iter-020 short-exact infrastructure on the iter-019 short complex) the named lemma $\HModulePrime\_\shortComplex\_\mathtt{shortExact}\,k\,S$ exposes an extension class $\mathtt{extClass} : \Ext\,(\HModulePrime\_\shortComplex\,k\,S).X_1\,(\HModulePrime\_\shortComplex\,k\,S).X_3\,1$ (Mathlib \texttt{Mathlib/Algebra/Homology/DerivedCategory/Ext/ExactSequences.lean}). Iter-021 uses it to build the connecting homomorphism $\delta : H^{n_0}(S.X_1) \to H^{n_1}(S.X_4)$ of the Mayer-Vietoris long exact sequence in $\ModuleCat\,k$-valued sheaf cohomology, mirroring Mathlib \texttt{Mathlib/CategoryTheory/Sites/SheafCohomology/MayerVietoris.lean} L112--114.

\begin{definition}[Connecting homomorphism $\delta$ of the MV-LES (iter-021)]
  \label{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_delta}
  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.HModule'_delta}
  \uses{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_shortComplex_shortExact, def:Scheme_HModule_prime_cohomologyPresheaf}
  Let $k$ be a field, $C$ a category equipped with a Grothendieck topology $J$ on which $\HasWeakSheafify\,J\,(\Type\,u)$, $\HasSheafify\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k)$, and $\HasExt\,(\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat.\{u\}\,k))$ all hold. Let $S : J.\MayerVietorisSquare$ be a Mayer-Vietoris square, $F : \Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)$, and $n_0, n_1 \in \mathbb N$ with $n_0 + 1 = n_1$. The \emph{connecting homomorphism} of the Mayer-Vietoris LES at degree $(n_0, n_1)$ is
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\delta : (\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{cohomologyPresheaf}\,k\,F\,n_0).\mathtt{obj}\,(\op\,S.X_1)
      \;\longrightarrow\;
      (\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{cohomologyPresheaf}\,k\,F\,n_1).\mathtt{obj}\,(\op\,S.X_4),
  \]
  i.e.\ a morphism in $\AddCommGrpCat$ from $H^{n_0}(S.X_1, F)$ to $H^{n_1}(S.X_4, F)$ in the $\ModuleCat\,k$-flavored cohomology theory of Section~\ref{sec:moduleK_cohomology_presheaf} (Definition~\ref{def:Scheme_HModule_prime_cohomologyPresheaf}).
\end{definition}

\begin{proof}
  \leanok
  Direct mirror of Mathlib L112--114 with $\AddCommGrpCat.\free \to \ModuleCat.\free\,k$. The body is a one-line term-mode expression
  \[
    \HModulePrime\_\delta\,k\,S\,F\,n_0\,n_1\,h \;:=\; \mathtt{AddCommGrpCat.ofHom}\,((\HModulePrime\_\shortComplex\_\mathtt{shortExact}\,k\,S).\mathtt{extClass}.\mathtt{precomp}\,\_\,(\mathtt{by\ omega})).
  \]
  Unpacking: $\mathtt{extClass} : \Ext\,(\HModulePrime\_\shortComplex\,k\,S).X_1\,(\HModulePrime\_\shortComplex\,k\,S).X_3\,1$ is the extension class accessor on $\HModulePrime\_\shortComplex\_\mathtt{shortExact}\,k\,S$ from Lemma~\ref{lem:Scheme_HModule_prime_shortComplex_shortExact}. Mathlib's $\mathtt{Ext.precomp}$ (\texttt{Mathlib/Algebra/Homology/DerivedCategory/Ext/ExactSequences.lean}) sends an extension class $\alpha : \Ext\,X\,Y\,a$, an object $Z$, and a proof $a + n = m$ to the precomposition map $\Ext\,Y\,Z\,n \to_{\mathrm{Add}} \Ext\,X\,Z\,m$. Specialising to $\alpha = \mathtt{extClass}$, $a = 1$, $Z = F$, $n = n_0$, $m = n_1$, and $h : 1 + n_0 = n_1$ (discharged by $\mathtt{omega}$ from the standing $n_0 + 1 = n_1$), we obtain a homomorphism $\Ext\,(\HModulePrime\_\shortComplex\,k\,S).X_3\,F\,n_0 \to_{\mathrm{Add}} \Ext\,(\HModulePrime\_\shortComplex\,k\,S).X_1\,F\,n_1$. Under the iter-016 per-fiber identifications $(\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{cohomologyPresheaf}\,k\,F\,n).\mathtt{obj}\,(\op\,X) = \HModulePrime\,k\,F\,n\,X$ (definitional $\mathtt{rfl}$, probe-verified), this is exactly the morphism in the signature.

  The outer $\mathtt{AddCommGrpCat.ofHom}$ wraps the resulting $\mathtt{AddMonoidHom}$ into a categorical morphism in $\AddCommGrpCat$, matching the codomain of $\HModulePrime\_\mathtt{cohomologyPresheaf}\,k\,F\,n$ which lands in $\AddCommGrpCat$ (forced by Mathlib's $\Abelian.\mathtt{extFunctor}\,n$ always landing there, regardless of $\Linear\,k$ enrichment; per-fiber $\Module\,k$ recovery is via the iter-014 $\HModulePrime$ reducibility, but the categorical morphism itself is $\AddCommGrpCat$-flavored). Plan-agent \texttt{lean\_run\_code} probe (iter-021) confirms the body typechecks end-to-end, kernel-only axioms.
\end{proof}

\begin{remark}[Why iter-021 scope is just $\delta$, not $\delta$+sequence+exactness]
  Mathlib's MV-LES build-out has the structure: $\delta$ (L112--114) $\to$ sequence (L120--122) $\to$ sequence-iso to $\Ext.\mathtt{contravariantSequence}$ (L124--138) $\to$ exactness theorem (L140--141) $\to$ $\delta$-zero $\mathtt{simp}$ companions (L143--149). The sequence-iso L124--138 is the technical heart: it requires four substantial auxiliary lemmas (L48--106) involving $\Ext.\mathtt{biprodAddEquiv}$ and the $\AddCommGrpCat$-side biproduct-vs-product addEquiv, all of which transfer to the $\ModuleCat\,k$ flavor but require careful handling of the per-fiber $\AddCommGrpCat$-vs-$\ModuleCat\,k$ distinction. Iter-021 lays only $\delta$ (the smallest useful unit downstream of iter-020); iter-022 will scaffold the sequence; iter-023 will scaffold the four auxiliary lemmas + the sequence-iso (the substantive multi-iteration work); iter-024 will scaffold the exactness theorem + the $\mathtt{simp}$ companions.

  This decomposition keeps each iteration to a tightly-coupled cohort with probe-confirmed bodies, matches the project's "one declaration cohort per iteration" cadence (now sustained for fifteen consecutive prover rounds, iter-006 through iter-021), and avoids inflating any single iteration beyond the standard scope. Total iter-021+ remaining LOC for the LES on $\Sheaf\,J\,(\ModuleCat\,k)$: $\sim$120 LOC of new infrastructure (vs Mathlib's $\sim$140 LOC for the $\AddCommGrpCat$-flavored version, the small reduction reflecting that iter-019/020's helpers consolidate two Mathlib gap-fills into one block each).

  Iter-021 sorry-count trajectory: $9 \to 10 \to 9$ (one new \lstinline{sorry} site in the $\HModulePrime\_\delta$ def; filled in the iter-021 prover round).
\end{remark}

